*{{flagicon|Belgium}} [[Belgium]]'s Foreign minister [[Steven Vanackere]] deplored the deaths. He hopes that the protest will strengthen the process of democratisation and the socio-economic reform in Egypt. He also pointed out the importance of freedom of speech and media.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://diplomatie.belgium.be/en/newsroom/news/press_releases/foreign_affairs/2011/01/ni_270111_vanackere_betogingen_egypte.jsp |title=Steven Vanackere on the situation in Egypt - Newsroom - Homepage - Foreign Affairs, Foreign Trade and Development Cooperation |publisher=Diplomatie.belgium.be |date= |accessdate=29 January 2011}}</ref>
*{{flagicon|Finland}} The Foreign Minister of [[Finland]] [[Alexander Stubb]], called [[Foreign Minister of Egypt]] [[Ahmed Aboul Gheit]] expressing Finland's strong hopes that the conflict is resolved peacefully. In a statement on the Finnish foreign ministry's website Stubb says among other things "Everyone should now strive to steady the situation quickly so that there would be no further fatalities or injuries. Finland condemns the use of force." He further expressed concern over the blocking of communications.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://formin.finland.fi/Public/default.aspx?contentid=211714&nodeid=15145&culture=en-US |title=Statement on the situation in Egypt by Foreign Minister Alexander Stubb - Ministry for Foreign Affairs of Finland: Current affairs |publisher=Formin.finland.fi |date= |accessdate=29 January 2011}}</ref>
